SIMPLE: emulgent
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Emulgent
<hw>E*mul"gent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>emulgens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>emulgere</ets> to milk out: cf. F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧mulgent</ets>. So called because regarded by the ancients
as straining out the serum, as if by milking, and so producing the
urine.]</ety> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Pertaining to the kidneys; renal;
<as>as, <ex>emulgent</ex> arteries and veins</as>.</def> --
<def2><pos>n.</pos> <def>An emulgent vessel, as a renal artery or
vein.</def></def2>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emulgent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Emulgent
<hw>E*mul"gent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A medicine
that excites the flow of bile.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Hoblyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Emulous</ent>⟦br⟧
